<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-07T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-07T13:00:00-05:00" n="498" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d498">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">714.44A15/141: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Des Portes</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-07T12:00:00-06:00">March 7,
                                1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>25. My telegram No. 24, March 5, 1 p.m. It is my considered opinion that
                            unless the British Government is willing to enlarge the terms of
                            reference there is grave danger of an immediate breakdown in the
                            negotiations. Please forward this opinion to Mr. Welles. The British
                            Minister is of the same opinion.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Des Portes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>